e was experienced through the eyes of a dog. Through the various domestic environments, controlled by humans, that the dog is subject to the viewer is asked to take note of the ripple effect that their actions may have. Details: This show takes place until October 6 at the South African State Theatre, 320 Pretorius Street, Pretoria Central. Tickets cost R100 to R110 and can be purchased from www.webtickets.co.za. For more information visit www.statetheatre.co.za Afrika Arts Festival: This multidisciplinary one-day festival features young artists who auditioned to participate. Following intensive preparations they will take to the stage to give patrons an array of dramatic art performances. Details: The festival takes place on October 5 at the Wits Theatre Complex, 24 Station Street, Johannesburg. Tickets cost R50 to R120 and can be purchased from www.webtickets.co.za. For more information visit www.wits.ac.za/WitsTheatre or call 011 717 1376 Current State of Poetry Showcase: This event brings established and upcoming poets together to celebrate poetry while some will take to the stage to offer the audience their prose. Details: The showcase takes place on October 5 at the Joburg Theatre, corner Simmonds Street & Stiemens Road Braamfontein. Tickets cost R100 and can be purchased from www.webtickets.co.za. For more information visit www.joburgtheatre.com Soweto Art and Craft Fair: One the first Saturday of every month Soweto’s artisans come out to sell their creations in the midst of local entertainment. The space looks to grow young businesses while offering a platform to young performers to acquaint themselves with the stage. Details: The fair takes place on October 5 at the Soweto Theatre, corner Bolani Link and Bolani Rd, Jabulani, Soweto. Tickets cost R20 and can be purchased from www.webtickets.co.za. For more information visit www.sowetotheatre.com or call 011 930 7461 The Bubbly Festival: Dress up and start your weekend with bubbles at the Shimmy Beach Club where ticket holders receive 10 tickets to taste whatever is on display. In addition to tasting patrons will receive live entertainment and food for all diet preferences. No under 18s allowed. Details: The festival takes place on October 5 at the Shimmy Beach Club, South Arm Road V&A Waterfront. Tickets cost R365 and can be purchased from www.quicket.co.za.  For more information visit www.shimmybeachclub.com or call 021 200 7778 Structural Response III: Central to Serge Alain Nitegeka’s work is the concept of forced migration. The artist brings issues of disrupted lives, work and spaces to the fore using building materials such as timber as commentary of the temporary nature of the structures that forced migrants construct and call home. Details: The exhibition is on until January 1 at the Norval Foundation, 4 Steenberg Road, Steenberg Estate. Entry costs R160 at the door or online. For more information visit www.norvalfoundation.org Pietermaritzburg Food Festival: Celebrate the diversity of South African cuisines and promote the growth of local business by bringing the whole family out for a day filled with arts and crafts, food and live entertainment. Details: The festival takes place on October 5 at the Golden Horse Casino, 45 New England Road Pietermaritzburg. Tickets cost R30 to R90 and can be purchased from Computicket. For more information visit www.goldenhorse.co.za or call 033 395 8136 HoptoberFest: More than 20 local breweries and distilleries come together alongside street food eateries and live entertainment for the whole family. Details: The festival takes place on October 5 at the Jonsson Kings Park Stadium, Jacko Jackson Drive, Stamford Hill, Durban. Tickets cost R50 to R120 and can be purchased from www.quicket.co.za. For more information visit www.hoptoberfest.co.za/